  "language": "English",
  "duration": 142.358375424,
  "text": " I just built a system that remembers my entire business so I don't have to. And it's pretty much running my life and keeping me on task. Here's what no one tells you about running a lot of things at once. It's confusing. I manage a brokerage with 300 agents. I build AI tools. I make content. And for years, the only place all of that actually lived was in my head. Every training thought, every half-built project, every idea at 2 a.m. My head was a hard drive, and at 55, it was absolutely stuffed full. AI did not fix that. At first, it made it worse, because now I could start five things in a day instead of one. More output, more loose ends, more stuff I was quietly afraid of dropping. I tried to fix it several times before, different note systems, reminders, emails to myself. But the problem each time was that I made myself the librarian, and nothing worked quite right. So I abandoned it. So this time I built it so that the AI is the librarian, not me. It has access to my calendars and my inboxes and tells me what actually matters every morning through a dashboard It aptly named my second brain By the way comment brain and I send you how mine works It knows every project I have and I'm working on, every video I ever posted, what I decided and why. I organize none of it. I start Claude every morning in my second brain and talk to it like my professional assistant. Some morning, I just ask it what actually matters today. Other times, it's log this or go sweep my folders for anything I forgot to file. And the best part is that all of it is in plain files on every device I own. I could forget the details on purpose and it wouldn't matter. I cannot overstate what this did to my stress. For the first time in years, I'm not holding all of it at once. I do not have to remember every single detail because something I trust now does. Now, I'm not going to lie, this is an advanced skill. I run most of it off a terminal window, not in a cloud or a codex desktop app. But man, is it ever worth learning these new AI skills to get there? We keep getting told AI is going to replace us. I think the truth is, it can help us carry the weight we were never meant to carry alone.",
